{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 15:59:18.748780", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall IP connectivity across the enterprise is healthy. OSPF adjacencies are established and routes are present end-to-end. Server farm hosts and the load balancer are reachable by IP and serve HTTP successfully when accessed via IP.\\n- Primary anomaly: DNS service on dns_server (10.200.0.2) is not running/listening, causing hostname resolution failures for clients. Consequently, web access by FQDN (e.g., web0.local, web99.local) fails, while access by IP works.\\n\\nEvidence and Findings\\n\\n1) Layer-3 Reachability and Routing\\n- End-to-end ping tests show 0% packet loss across sampled pairs (get_reachability). Hosts and servers, including load_balancer (10.200.0.7) and web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6), are reachable.\\n- Targeted pings:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 → dns_server (10.200.0.2): 0% loss, avg ~3.34 ms\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 → load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 0% loss, avg ~3.04 ms\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 → dns_server/load_balancer: 0% loss; similar RTTs\\n- FRR OSPF status:\\n  - OSPF neighbors are Full on router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, and server_access_router toward their core neighbors.\\n  - Routing tables on core, distribution, and server_access_router include all expected 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 client subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 server net via OSPF with reasonable metrics. No missing routes observed.\\n\\n2) Host Configuration\\n- DHCP appears to be operational; hosts have correct addressing and default gateways:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.10/24, default via 10.1.1.1\\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.12/24, default via 10.2.1.1\\n- Resolver configuration on both hosts:\\n  - /etc/resolv.conf points to nameserver 10.200.0.2 (dns_server).\\n\\n3) DNS Functionality (Anomalous)\\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - nslookup web0.local 10.200.0.2 and nslookup web99.local 10.200.0.2 → “connection refused … no servers could be reached”\\n- On dns_server itself:\\n  - netstat shows no process listening on UDP/TCP port 53. Only 127.0.0.11 ephemeral is present; no DNS daemon bound to 10.200.0.2:53.\\n- Name resolution on clients therefore fails:\\n  - curl to http://web0.local and http://web99.local returns HTTP code 000 (failure).\\n- Access by IP addresses works:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1:\\n    - curl http://10.200.0.3 (web_server_0) → 200 OK\\n    - curl http://10.200.0.7 (load_balancer) → 200 OK\\n  - host_2_1_1_1:\\n    - curl http://10.200.0.3 → 200 OK\\n    - curl http://10.200.0.7 → 200 OK\\n- This isolates the issue to DNS service availability rather than routing or server application health.\\n\\n4) Web and Load Balancer Health\\n- ICMP to all published web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6) and load_balancer (10.200.0.7) succeeds from both hosts.\\n- HTTP over IP returns 200 OK with reasonable TTFB/total times, indicating the web servers and load balancer are up and reachable.\\n- By network design, backend web servers behind the load balancer are not directly exposed; this behavior was not contradicted by tests.\\n\\nLocalization\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Fault domain: Application/service layer on the DNS server, not the network fabric.\\n- Supporting evidence: nslookup attempts from clients receive “connection refused”; dns_server has no listener on port 53; resolvers on clients point to this DNS.\\n\\nRoot Cause\\n- DNS daemon on dns_server is down/not listening, resulting in refusal of DNS queries and breaking name resolution for local FQDNs (e.g., web0.local, web99.local). All other infrastructure (OSPF, routing, server IP reachability, HTTP services) is functioning normally.\\n\\nImpact Assessment\\n- All hosts relying on 10.200.0.2 for DNS cannot resolve local service names (web0.local–web3.local, web99.local).\\n- IP-based access continues to function; therefore, the outage is constrained to DNS resolution rather than network or server connectivity.\\n\\nNo remediation steps are proposed per request., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='239ee954-27b6-4fcf-b263-30e2a42676d1'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
